Sure, here's the program in Python:

number = float(input("Enter a floating-point number: "))

integer_part = int(number)
right_most_digit = integer_part % 10

print("The right-most digit of the integral part is:", right_most_digit)


This program prompts the user to enter a floating-point number, then converts it to an integer using the int() function. It then calculates the right-most digit of the integer by taking the modulo % of the integer by 10. Finally, it displays the right-most digit to the user.

Sure, here's the program in JavaScript:

const number = parseFloat(prompt("Enter a floating-point number: "));
const integerpart = parseInt(number);
const rightmostdigit = integerpart % 10;

console.log("The right-most digit of the integral part is: " + rightmostdigit);


This program uses the parseFloat() function to prompt the user to enter a floating-point number as a string, and then converts it to a floating-point number. It then uses the parseInt() function to convert the floating-point number to an integer, and finally calculates the right-most digit of the integer by taking the modulo % of the integer by 10. Finally, it displays the right-most digit to the user using console.log().
